29:11.240 --> 29:17.080
This is the full description for the fundamental group of SO3.

29:17.080 --> 29:21.240
Now, if we symbolically replace id with zero

29:21.240 --> 29:27.960
and p with one, then this table begins to look a little familiar.

29:28.760 --> 29:31.960
Specifically, we can see that the fundamental group

29:31.960 --> 29:41.080
of SO3 is just the integer's modulo 2, also known as z mod 2.

29:42.680 --> 29:47.800
Think about all of the beautiful mathematics summed up in this equation.

29:47.800 --> 29:53.000
The whole Dirac belt trick is just a demonstration of the fact that the

29:53.000 --> 29:59.240
fundamental group of the space of rotations is z mod 2.

29:59.480 --> 30:04.040
Now, if you'll indulge me for a moment, I'd like to talk about what makes

30:04.040 --> 30:08.840
mathematics so non-trivial. SO3 is a good example of the kind of

30:08.840 --> 30:12.360
object you see in math. You can think of it as a group,

30:12.360 --> 30:17.080
and you can think of it as a topological space.

30:17.080 --> 30:20.120
Therefore, we can study it using group theory,

30:20.120 --> 30:24.600
or we can study it using topology. Often in mathematics,

30:24.600 --> 30:27.480
you start by thinking about an object in one way,

30:27.480 --> 30:31.880
and then discover you can think about it in a completely different way.

30:31.880 --> 30:35.880
And, crucially, all the different ways to think about an object

30:35.880 --> 30:40.600
interact with each other. So, the group theory has implications for the

30:40.600 --> 30:46.360
topology, and the topology has implications for the group theory.

30:47.560 --> 30:51.160
Let's give a summary of part three.

30:51.160 --> 30:57.320
A group is a set with an operation that satisfies a handful of rules.

30:57.320 --> 31:01.720
