denoted SO3. Every topological space has a group

31:09.720 --> 31:13.080
associated with it, called its fundamental group,

31:13.080 --> 31:18.120
which is the set of paths which start and end at a base point.

31:18.120 --> 31:23.240
The fundamental group of SO3 is z mod 2.

31:27.960 --> 31:38.200
It's finally time to discuss spin in quantum mechanics.

31:38.200 --> 31:43.400
You're probably used to thinking of vectors with an x, y, and z component.

31:43.400 --> 31:47.320
Normally, we'd say that vectors are elements of the set R3,

31:47.320 --> 31:50.680
because they're comprised of three real numbers.

31:50.680 --> 31:53.640
However, quantum spin vectors are a little different.

31:53.640 --> 31:56.760
They're instead comprised of two complex numbers,

31:56.840 --> 31:59.720
where here alpha and beta are the complex numbers,

31:59.720 --> 32:04.440
and thus we say that they are elements of the set C2.

32:04.440 --> 32:08.440
Remember that a complex number can be written as a plus bi,

32:08.440 --> 32:11.640
where a is the real part and b is the imaginary part.

32:11.640 --> 32:15.240
We can also write it as r times e to the i theta,

32:15.240 --> 32:18.760
using Euler's formula to express it in terms of a

32:18.760 --> 32:24.120
magnitude r and an angle theta. The other thing about complex numbers is

32:24.120 --> 32:26.520
that they can be quote-unquote conjugated.

32:26.520 --> 32:32.840
So, for instance, the conjugate of alpha would be a minus bi.

32:32.840 --> 32:35.960
Finally, the absolute value squared of a complex number

32:35.960 --> 32:38.440
is just the number times its conjugate,

32:38.440 --> 32:45.160
which is equal to a squared plus b squared, also known as r squared.

32:45.160 --> 32:49.560
Now, what do these complex numbers correspond to in the physical world?

32:49.560 --> 32:53.240
Well, say you had an electron whose spin vector had the components

32:53.240 --> 32:57.560
of alpha and beta. If you measure the direction of the

32:57.560 --> 33:01.720
electron's spin along the z-axis, then the probability that you find

33:01.720 --> 33:06.360
it to be spin up will be the absolute value of alpha squared.

33:06.360 --> 33:09.720
Meanwhile, the probability that you find it to be spin down

33:09.720 --> 33:13.640
will be the absolute value of beta squared.

33:13.640 --> 33:17.560
So, for instance, the state with components one and zero

33:17.560 --> 33:20.840
will be measured to be spin up 100 percent of the time,

33:20.920 --> 33:24.760
while the state with components zero and one will be measured to be

33:24.760 --> 33:28.920
spin down 100 percent of the time.

33:31.720 --> 33:35.560
Notice that, because all probabilities must sum to one,

33:35.560 --> 33:39.640
the absolute value of alpha squared plus the absolute value of beta squared

33:39.640 --> 33:42.760
must be equal to one.

33:44.760 --> 33:49.480
Now, as we discussed previously, vectors in r3 have an inner product where you

33:49.480 --> 33:54.120
take the transpose of one vector and multiply it by the other.

33:54.120 --> 33:57.880
Quantum spin vectors, however, have an inner product where you take the

33:57.880 --> 34:03.960
conjugate transpose of one vector and then multiply it by the other.

34:05.000 --> 34:09.400
Just to be clear, in order to take the conjugate transpose of a spin vector,

34:09.400 --> 34:13.320
you just complex conjugate the components and turn the column vector

34:13.320 --> 34:16.360
into a row vector.

34:17.160 --> 34:21.080
Now, you can use this inner product in order to extract the components of these

34:21.080 --> 34:24.920
spin vectors. For instance, the inner product of one

34:24.920 --> 34:31.240
zero with alpha beta is just alpha. Likewise, the inner product of zero

34:31.240 --> 34:36.040
one with alpha beta is just beta.

34:37.640 --> 34:40.760
Therefore, the probability to measure an electron to be

34:40.760 --> 34:44.840
spin up with respect to the z-axis is the absolute value squared

34:44.840 --> 34:49.080
of the inner product of the spin up state with alpha beta.

34:49.080 --> 34:53.800
Likewise, the probability to be spin down with respect to the z-axis

34:53.800 --> 34:57.240
is the absolute value squared of the inner product of the spin

34:57.240 --> 35:00.760
down state with alpha beta.

35:03.800 --> 35:07.400
Now, there's nothing fundamentally special about the z-axis.

35:07.400 --> 35:11.880
Here, I'll write the spin up and down states with respect to the x-axis

35:11.880 --> 35:18.280
and y-axis as well. So, the probability of a state to be, say,

35:18.280 --> 35:22.600
measured spin down along the y-axis will be the absolute value squared

35:22.600 --> 35:27.400
of the inner product of the spin down y-state with alpha beta.

35:27.400 --> 35:31.720
And likewise, you would have the same thing for being, say, spin up along the x-axis

35:31.720 --> 35:34.520
or what have you.

35:37.240 --> 35:40.200
So, whereas the inner product of position vectors

35:40.200 --> 35:44.360
is used to find lengths and angles, the inner product of our complex two

35:44.360 --> 35:50.600
dimensional spin vectors is used to find the probabilities of measurements.

35:51.960 --> 35:55.160
Now, we can also use the inner product to re-express

35:55.160 --> 35:59.160
another equation that we've seen. Remember that the condition that

35:59.160 --> 36:03.320
probabilities must sum to one implies that the absolute value of alpha

36:03.320 --> 36:07.400
squared plus the absolute value of beta squared must be equal to one.

36:07.400 --> 36:11.240
This is equivalent to saying that the inner product of a spin vector

36:11.240 --> 36:15.880
with itself must be equal to one. When we have this condition,

36:15.880 --> 36:19.880
we say that our spin vector is properly normalized or that we have a

36:19.880 --> 36:22.680
physical state.

36:26.040 --> 36:29.960
Now, let's talk about rotations. As we discussed earlier,

36:29.960 --> 36:34.040
rotations act on vectors as three by three matrices.

36:34.040 --> 36:38.360
In order to rotate a spin vector, however, we'll instead have to use a two

36:38.360 --> 36:42.920
by two matrix with complex entries. We'll label this matrix with the

36:42.920 --> 36:46.920
letter u. Remember that our rotation matrix

36:46.920 --> 36:50.440
needed to satisfy the condition that the transpose of the matrix

36:50.440 --> 36:53.960
times the matrix itself must be equal to the identity.

36:53.960 --> 36:59.320
What is the analogous condition that this new matrix u must satisfy?

37:00.200 --> 37:06.520
First off, rotating a spin vector shouldn't change the inner product of it

37:06.520 --> 37:09.640
with itself. Because if that starts off as one, then it

37:09.640 --> 37:15.080
should remain one after being rotated. In order for this to hold, we must have

37:15.080 --> 37:19.240
that the conjugate transpose of u times u

37:19.240 --> 37:23.720
is equal to the identity matrix. When we have this condition,

37:23.720 --> 37:28.520
we say that u is a unitary matrix.

37:31.400 --> 37:35.560
Now, aside from being unitary, there's one other slightly technical condition

37:35.560 --> 37:40.280
that we need to put on u. First, note that the spin vectors with the

37:40.280 --> 37:44.280
components of alpha, beta, and e to the i theta alpha,

37:44.280 --> 37:48.600
e to the i theta beta, have no observable differences.

37:48.600 --> 37:52.200
So, for example, when calculating the probability

37:52.200 --> 37:55.800
that the second state is spin up along the z-axis,

37:55.800 --> 37:59.080
the e to the i theta makes no difference in the final answer,

37:59.080 --> 38:03.880
because you're just taking the absolute value squared of that inner product.

38:03.880 --> 38:06.920
Physicists tend to call this factor of e to the i theta

38:06.920 --> 38:12.280
a phase. Anyway, this implies that the matrix u

38:12.280 --> 38:18.760
and e to the i theta times u correspond to the exact same transformation.

38:18.760 --> 38:22.120
Therefore, to get rid of this redundancy, we can choose

38:22.120 --> 38:26.280
for the determinant of u to be equal to one.

38:26.280 --> 38:29.720
Finally, we denote the set of all such matrices u

38:29.720 --> 38:35.960
that satisfy these conditions as su2. The two refers to the fact that the

38:35.960 --> 38:39.560
matrices are two-dimensional, the u refers to the fact that they're

38:39.560 --> 38:43.880
unitary, and the s stands for special, which means that the matrices have

38:43.880 --> 38:46.440
determinant one.

38:50.040 --> 38:56.680
So, to summarize part four, quantum spin states are vectors in c2.

38:56.680 --> 39:00.360
The inner product of spin vectors involves taking the conjugate transpose

39:00.360 --> 39:04.360
of one vector and multiplying it by the second one.

39:04.360 --> 39:07.720
There are states which are always spin up or spin down

39:07.720 --> 39:11.160
when measured with respect to certain directions in space.

39:11.160 --> 39:14.600
The probability that a state will be spin up in some direction

39:14.600 --> 39:18.520
will be the absolute value squared of its inner product with the spin up

39:18.520 --> 39:21.800
vector. In order to rotate a spin state, you

39:21.800 --> 39:27.080
must act on it by a matrix u in su2.

39:27.320 --> 39:41.960
Earlier, we got acquainted with s03 as a topological space.

39:41.960 --> 39:45.400
So, what about su2?

39:47.160 --> 39:50.280
Well, first let's write the 2 by 2 matrix u

39:50.280 --> 39:54.440
and call its four entries a, b, c, and d.

39:54.440 --> 39:57.800
Now, remember that u conjugate transpose times u

39:57.800 --> 40:02.680
must be equal to the identity matrix. This is equivalent to saying that u

40:02.680 --> 40:07.320
conjugate transpose must be equal to u inverse.

40:07.320 --> 40:11.560
If we write out this equation explicitly

40:11.560 --> 40:17.080
and use the fact that the determinant of u is equal to one,

40:17.080 --> 40:20.680
then after staring at this verbit, we realize that d

40:20.680 --> 40:24.840
must be equal to the conjugate of a, and c must be equal to

40:24.840 --> 40:29.080
minus the conjugate of b. Plugging these equations back in,

40:29.080 --> 40:32.680
we see that u must have the entries of a, b,

40:32.680 --> 40:38.040
