50:29.480 --> 50:34.520
which is just the length squared of r. If we multiply this matrix by u on the

50:34.520 --> 50:37.960
left and the conjugate transpose of u on the right,

50:37.960 --> 50:42.040
the overall matrix will still be traceless and self-adjoint.

50:42.040 --> 50:45.480
Furthermore, its determinant will be unchanged.

50:45.480 --> 50:49.560
Therefore, we can write this new matrix as a new position vector,

50:49.560 --> 50:53.640
which we call r prime, dotted with the polymatrices.

50:53.640 --> 50:56.680
Because r and r prime must have the same length,

50:56.680 --> 51:01.320
r prime must just be a rotated version of r.

51:01.320 --> 51:06.600
So the rotation matrix, uppercase r, is just whatever three-by-three matrix

51:06.600 --> 51:10.520
satisfies the equation r prime equals uppercase r

51:10.520 --> 51:15.240
times r. This is how you convert an SU2 matrix u

51:15.240 --> 51:22.440
into an SO3 matrix r. Now notice that u and negative u

51:22.440 --> 51:26.440
map to the exact same rotation.

51:27.160 --> 51:30.680
This is how we can see that SU2 really is a double cover

51:30.680 --> 51:33.400
of SO3.

51:34.200 --> 51:37.720
Finally, I should just mention that there's this really useful explicit

51:37.720 --> 51:42.520
formula for the SU2 matrix u corresponding to a rotation

51:42.520 --> 51:45.720
given an axis n hat and an angle of rotation

51:45.720 --> 51:51.160
theta. Namely, u equals cosine of theta over 2

51:51.160 --> 51:55.080
times the identity matrix plus sine of theta over 2

51:55.080 --> 52:00.040
times negative i n hat dot the polymatrices.

52:00.040 --> 52:05.000
Notice that if we plug in theta equals 2 pi, then u equals negative the identity

52:05.000 --> 52:08.600
matrix, meaning a 2 pi rotation does negate the spin

52:08.600 --> 52:12.840
vector of an electron. We can also write this using matrix

52:12.840 --> 52:15.640
exponentiation, but let's not get into that.

52:15.640 --> 52:19.640
Oof, glad I got that out of my chest.

52:29.560 --> 52:33.560
Now, there are a few things you're probably wondering about.

52:33.560 --> 52:37.640
First off, how do you actually rotate an electron?

52:37.640 --> 52:42.440
Clearly, you can't just pick it up and rotate it like it's a tennis ball.

52:42.440 --> 52:46.520
There are two ways to answer this question. The first is that

52:46.520 --> 52:50.040
you can think of a rotation as the result of changing

52:50.040 --> 52:55.480
reference frames. For example, say you have your electron,

52:55.480 --> 53:00.200
put it on a table, and put that table in a room.

53:00.200 --> 53:05.720
If you then walk around the electron and continuously describe its quantum spin

53:05.720 --> 53:16.120
state using your own reference frame,

53:17.240 --> 53:20.360
then when you've finished walking 2 pi radians around it,

53:20.360 --> 53:24.760
the state of the electron will be negative. Now,

53:24.760 --> 53:28.600
that's all fine and good, but there's also a more concrete way to rotate an

53:28.600 --> 53:32.440
electron. You see, an electron's spin will create

53:32.440 --> 53:36.280
an angular momentum vector which points in some direction.

53:36.280 --> 53:40.600
If you then expose this electron to an external magnetic field,

53:40.600 --> 53:44.680
it'll cause the angular momentum vector to rotate around the magnetic field

53:44.680 --> 53:48.840
vector in a process known as Larmor procession.

53:48.840 --> 53:53.160
Therefore, you can use magnetic fields to rotate electrons.

53:53.160 --> 53:56.680
Here's something else you might be wondering. Is there any way we could

53:56.760 --> 54:02.200
experimentally detect the minus sign which comes from a 2 pi rotation?

54:02.200 --> 54:09.160
Amazingly, the answer is yes. Here's how. First, take your electron and then

54:09.160 --> 54:14.120
put it in a quantum superposition at two different locations.

54:14.120 --> 54:19.160
Then, subject one of them to a magnetic field, rotating it by 2 pi radians,

54:19.160 --> 54:25.080
inducing the minus sign. Finally, recombine the electrons.

54:25.080 --> 54:30.200
In the end, you'll find interference effects stemming from the minus sign.

54:30.200 --> 54:33.640
This exact thing has actually already been done with neutrons.

54:33.640 --> 54:37.960
Look up neutron interferometry for more details.

54:37.960 --> 54:43.480
So, way back when I said that an overall phase has no observable consequences,

54:43.480 --> 54:47.800
I was being a bit imprecise. You can detect overall phases in quantum

54:47.800 --> 54:50.840
mechanics, but only if you make superpositions and

54:50.840 --> 54:55.320
create interference experiments. Here's something else I wanted to tell

54:55.320 --> 54:59.800
you about. Real projective space. If you take the

54:59.800 --> 55:03.560
two sphere and identify antipodal points as the same

55:03.560 --> 55:06.840
point, you create a topological space known as

55:06.840 --> 55:12.600
RP2 or two-dimensional real projective space.

55:13.160 --> 55:17.880
To reiterate, every pair of antipodal points on the two sphere

55:17.880 --> 55:24.280
is just one point in RP2. We can write this in the language of

55:24.280 --> 55:29.640
equivalence relations by saying that RP2 is s2 modulo the

55:29.640 --> 55:34.200
equivalence relation that the point x, y, z is the same as

55:34.200 --> 55:40.440
negative x, negative y, negative z. Now, this construction directly extends

55:40.440 --> 55:45.880
to the three sphere. So, RP3 is just s3 modulo the equivalence

55:45.880 --> 55:49.480
relation that antipodal points on the three sphere

55:49.480 --> 55:55.160
are identified with each other. The relevance this has for us is that

55:55.160 --> 56:01.160
topologically, s03 is RP3. This goes hand in hand with

56:01.160 --> 56:05.480
s2 being s3 and gives us another way to understand

56:05.480 --> 56:10.440
how s02 is the double cover of s03.

56:10.760 --> 56:16.040
On the subject of this covering space business, let me point out that while

56:16.040 --> 56:21.400
the fundamental group of s03 is z mod2, the fundamental group of s02

56:21.400 --> 56:24.760
is the trivial group, the group with only one element, which is because all

56:24.760 --> 56:28.120
paths can be contracted on the three sphere.

56:28.120 --> 56:32.840
Note that the fundamental group of s03 then has twice the number of elements

56:32.840 --> 56:37.480
as the fundamental group of s02. This fact is intimately related to the

56:37.480 --> 56:43.720
fact that s02 is a double cover of s03 and not, say, a triple cover.

56:43.720 --> 56:46.920
If this stuff intrigues you, you should probably go learn some algebraic

56:46.920 --> 56:49.560
topology.

